          "type": "text",
          "text": "Perfect! ✅ Circuit built successfully. Here's your counter:\n\n### **Wiring Table**\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| D2 | 7-segment (seg A) | via R_A (220Ω) |\n| D3 | 7-segment (seg B) | via R_B (220Ω) |\n| D4 | 7-segment (seg C) | via R_C (220Ω) |\n| D5 | 7-segment (seg D) | via R_D (220Ω) |\n| D6 | 7-segment (seg E) | via R_E (220Ω) |\n| D7 | 7-segment (seg F) | via R_F (220Ω) |\n| D8 | 7-segment (seg G) | via R_G (220Ω) |\n| D9 | Button (pin A) | Button input (INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| GND | 7-segment (GND) + Button (pin B) | Ground rail |\n\n### **How It Works**\n- Each time you press the button, the counter increments by 1 and displays 0–9 on the 7-segment.\n- When it reaches 9 and you press again, it wraps back to 0.\n- The sketch uses a lookup table to drive the correct segments for each digit.\n- 220Ω series resistors protect each segment (~20mA max per segment at 5V).\n\n### **Power Budget**\n- **Per-pin**: D2–D8 each sink ~20mA (7 segments × 20mA = 140mA total, well within Arduino's 200mA rail limit)\n- **D9 (button input)**: <1mA (input only, external pull-up via 10kΩ on-chip)\n- **Total board draw**: ~145mA (safe for USB or external 5V supply)\n\nYour counter is ready! Press the button to test. 🎉"
        }
      ]
    }
